{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"591173a7-e252-4ba4-939f-567b133e1a36","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's a summary:\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\nMSTest v4 changed the **test ID generation** to use fully qualified names. Azure DevOps sees these as brand-new tests. To restore history, add a `.runsettings` file with the legacy strategy:\n\n```xml\n<RunSettings>\n  <MSTest>\n    <TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n  </MSTest>\n</RunSettings>\n```\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is now a **class-level context** — it's no longer tied to a specific test. Accessing `TestName` throws because class init runs once for the entire class, not per-test. Your `SetupTests.cs` line 13 hits this directly.\n\n**Fix:** Remove or guard that access:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in MSTest v4\n    // Move test-specific logic to [TestInitialize] instead\n}\n```\n\n### 3. Other v4 changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **Parallel execution** | Now enabled *per class* by default; tests in the same class may run concurrently. Set `[Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.MethodLevel)]` or disable explicitly if you have shared state. |\n| **`Assert.AreEqual` on doubles** | Floating-point tolerance overloads are stricter; implicit widening no longer masks precision issues. |\n| **`[DataRow]` type coercion** | Implicit conversions (e.g., `int` → `long`) that previously \"just worked\" may now fail. Use exact types. |\n| **`TestContext.Properties`** | Read-only in class/assembly init contexts. |\n| **`[DeploymentItem]`** | Copies are no longer made by default; set `<DeploymentEnabled>true</DeploymentEnabled>` in `.runsettings` if you depend on this. |\n\nWould you like me to fix `SetupTests.cs` (e.g., move the `TestName` access to a `[TestInitialize]` method)?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d69e111c-74c0-464b-bac6-8ea3dfcee86b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I can give a comprehensive answer about MSTest v4 breaking changes based on my knowledge.\n\nKey MSTest v4 breaking changes:\n\n1. **Test ID change (fully qualified test IDs)** — MSTest v4 changed how test IDs are computed. They now use fully qualified names by default. This causes Azure DevOps (and other CI systems) to see them as entirely new tests, losing history. The fix is to set `<TestIdGenerationStrategy>` in the `.runsettings` file to use the legacy strategy, or accept the new IDs.\n\n2. **TestContext in ClassInitialize** — In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` methods no longer carries test-specific information like `TestName`. \n\nThe context is now class-level rather than test-level, so accessing `TestContext.TestName` will throw or return null since `ClassInitialize` runs once for the entire class, not per individual test.\n\n3. Other breaking changes include `[DataRow]` type coercion differences, floating point assertion behavior, parallel execution shifts, `DeploymentItem` handling, and read-only `TestContext.Properties` in certain scenarios.\n\nLet me look at the specific issue in line 13 of SetupTests.cs.","outputTokens":903},"id":"4213bb1f-2097-4b35-897d-0863ae118248","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:25:22.854Z","parentId":"c4798df3-476d-45d6-badf-8d748e495c5d"}
